3.4.0 Constitutional Purpose
The Causality Coordination Object (CCO) governs how the system interprets the cause of a disruption.
It exists to:
●Maintain legal defensibility

●Preserve interpretive transparency

●Support versioned routing recommendations

●Enable dual-branch evaluation

●Prevent narrative-only override

●Ensure deterministic replay

Every Incident must have exactly one CausalityObject (CCO root).
 Every evaluation references a specific immutable CausalityVersion.

3.4.1 Object Structure
CausalityObject (root identity)
●cco_object_id (UUID)

●incident_id (UUID)

●created_at

●locked (boolean default false)

This object never changes identity.

CausalityVersion (immutable)
Each version contains:
●cco_version_id (UUID)

●cco_object_id

●branch_type:

○SYSTEM_PRIMARY

○USER_ASSERTION

●cause_label_public:

○Weather

○Airline Operations

○Maintenance / Mechanical

○Airport Operations

○Government Restriction

○Unknown / Pending

●cause_class_internal:

○INTERNAL

○EXTERNAL

○MIXED

○UNKNOWN

●confidence_tier:

○LOW

○MEDIUM

○HIGH

●evidence_support_set (array of evidence_ids)

●supersedes_version_id (nullable)

●is_active (boolean)

Only one CausalityVersion may be active at a time.
All prior versions remain historically valid.

3.4.2 Versioning Doctrine
Causality evolves.
Triggers for new CausalityVersion:
●New evidence materially affects interpretation.

●User assertion supported by evidence.

●Dual-branch initiated.

●Jurisdiction update materially affects classification.

No destructive overwrite permitted.
The active_cco_version_id on Incident must always point to the current version.

3.4.3 Evidence Threshold Rule
User cannot override system classification without evidence.
Override Flow:
1.User disputes classification.

2.System soft-blocks:
 “Supporting evidence required to proceed with alternate interpretation.”

3.Upon evidence submission:

○New USER_ASSERTION branch created.

○Both SYSTEM_PRIMARY and USER_ASSERTION branches active.


3.4.4 Dual Branch Doctrine
Dual branch occurs when:
●User assertion supported by evidence conflicts with system classification.

During dual branch:
●Both versions remain active candidates.

●Routing evaluation may compute results for both.

●Confidence tiers displayed.

Collapse Rule:
When evidence confidence threshold is HIGH:
●The weaker branch is superseded.

●Only one branch remains active.

●Historical branch remains preserved.

●No special collapse event required; supersedence chain preserves integrity.


3.4.5 Routing Integration Contract
Every RoutingRecommendation version must reference:
●incident_id

●cco_version_id

Routing must use only the active CCO version at evaluation time.
If CCO changes:
●New RoutingRecommendation version must be generated.


3.4.6 Trip Context Interaction
One Incident = One Primary Disruption Domain.
Multiple Incidents on same Trip may:
●Reference each other via linked_incident_ids

●Influence sequencing recommendations

CausalityObjects remain independent.

3.4.7 Customer-Facing Language Rule
The term “External” must never appear customer-facing.
Public labels must use friendly taxonomy:
●Weather

●Airline Operations

●Maintenance / Mechanical

●Airport Operations

●Government Restriction

●Unknown / Pending

Internal classification remains available for routing logic.

3.4.8 Locking Doctrine
CCO locks when:
●All claims tied to the Incident are resolved

●No open dispute remains

Exception Handling:
If new material evidence appears post-resolution:
●New CausalityVersion may be created

●CCO may be reopened

Reopen must be event-logged.

3.4.9 Deterministic Replay Contract
To reconstruct causality state:
Required:
●incident_created

●all evidence_upload_completed

●causality_version_created (all)

●routing_recommendation_created (all versions)

●claim events

Replay must follow supersedes chain to determine active state at any historical timestamp.

