3.4.11 — Cross-Feature Integration Contracts
The Causality Coordination Object (CCO) is not an isolated interpretive structure.
 It is a foundational arbitration layer that feeds and constrains multiple system components.
This section formally declares upstream requirements and downstream consumers.

A. Upstream Dependencies (What 3.4 Requires)
1️⃣ Section 3.1 — Incident OS
CCO lifecycle is governed by Incident lifecycle rules:
●Review entry requires evidence (3.1.4).

●Late evidence triggers CCO re-evaluation.

●Dual-branch collapse must occur during Review evaluation.

●Locking and reopening rules originate in Incident state transitions.

CCO may not mutate outside Incident-controlled evaluation triggers.

2️⃣ Section 3.2 — Core Data Objects
CCO requires:
●Immutable Evidence objects.

●Incident.primary_disruption_domain.

●Incident.jurisdiction fields.

●Incident.active_cco_version_id pointer.

●Event ledger integrity.

CCO must never exist without an Incident.
 Incident must never exist without a CCO object.

3️⃣ Section 9.4 — Interpretive Traceability (ITR)
Every CausalityVersion creation must generate:
●Interpretive Trace Record.

●Evidence set snapshot.

●Confidence tier justification.

●Supersedence reference (if applicable).

Replay must be possible without heuristic reconstruction.

4️⃣ Jurisdiction Mapping Layer
CCO evaluation requires:
●incident_jurisdiction_id

●jurisdiction_ambiguous flag

●policy governing jurisdiction data

Jurisdiction ambiguity may trigger dual-branch causality evaluation.

B. Downstream Consumers (What 3.4 Feeds)
1️⃣ Section 3.1 — Incident OS Behavior
CCO status affects:
●Whether Review can proceed.

●Whether dual-branch is active.

●Whether collapse may occur.

●Whether Incident can lock.

●Whether Action stage can generate routing.

Incident state transitions must respect active_cco_version_id.

2️⃣ Section 3.3 — Coverage Graph Model (Critical)
Coverage Graph evaluation must read:
●CCO.cause_label_public

●CCO.cause_class_internal

●CCO.confidence_tier

●CCO.jurisdiction state

Coverage prioritization must incorporate causality.
Example:
●Weather → airline compensation not primary.

●Airline Operations → airline remediation first.

●Government restriction → jurisdiction override.

Coverage Graph must not compute eligibility without referencing active CCO version.

3️⃣ RoutingRecommendation Engine
Each RoutingRecommendation version must:
●Bind to cco_version_id.

●Snapshot cause_label_public.

●Snapshot confidence_tier.

If CCO changes:
●New RoutingRecommendation version required.

●Previous versions remain historically valid.

RoutingRecommendation must never reference a mutable causality state.

4️⃣ Claims Sequencing Engine
Claim order and advisories depend on CCO.
Examples:
●Airline fault → Airline claim suggested first.

●Weather → Insurance or credit card suggested first.

●Mixed cause → advisory branch logic required.

Claims must reference the CCO version active at creation time.

5️⃣ Section 8.4 — Audit & Event Ledger
CCO version creation and supersedence must emit:
●causality_version_created

●causality_version_superseded

Collapse is represented through version supersedence, not a distinct collapse event.
Audit reconstruction must determine active branch solely via supersedence chain.

6️⃣ Section 15 — Stress Testing & Scenario Hardening
Stress simulations must validate:
●Conflicting evidence injection.

●Malicious narrative without evidence.

●Rapid successive causality changes.

●Dual-branch activation and collapse.

●Jurisdiction toggling.

●High-confidence override scenarios.

Stress tests must verify:
●Only one active CCO version at a time.

●Superseded versions preserved.

●Routing recomputation integrity.


7️⃣ Surge Mode Integration
In PROTECTIVE or ELEVATED modes:
●CCO re-evaluation may be queued.

●Dual-branch evaluation may defer heavy computations.

●Active CCO version must remain stable until evaluation completes.

No partial CCO state may be visible.

C. Global Invariants
The following invariants are system-wide:
1.Exactly one CausalityObject per Incident.

2.At least one CausalityVersion per CCO.

3.Only one active CausalityVersion at any time.

4.No destructive deletion of historical versions.

5.Routing must reference immutable CCO version.

6.Customer-facing labels must not expose internal classification terms.

7.Evidence required for user assertion branch creation.

8.Collapse occurs only when confidence threshold is HIGH.

Violation of any invariant constitutes governance failure.
